commit_message:
Fix Nova grenade upgrade problem

In I1479f37f500a358cdf7ad416f0257288b65c9245, oslo.middleware
finally got rid of the oslo namespace. We should fix the
api-paste.ini from kilo when it gets upgraded to newer versions
of openstack with new oslo.middleware versions.


Change-Id: Ib78b4252b6b1213e497b2365698edbc955c111d2

commit_message:
Fix Nova grenade upgrade problem

In I1479f37f500a358cdf7ad416f0257288b65c9245, oslo.middleware
finally got rid of the oslo namespace. We should fix the
api-paste.ini from kilo when it gets upgraded to newer versions
of openstack with new oslo.middleware versions.

Change-Id: Ib78b4252b6b1213e497b2365698edbc955c111d2

This patch:

* Removes `address` for `local` role. `address` is not required

commit_message:
Fix dump for PostgreSQL is missing in a snapshot

This patch:

* Removes `address` for `local` role. `address` is not required
anymore for task execution for this role;

* Fixes missing dump for PostgreSQL;

* Explicitly specifies `hostname` for a master. As the result we will
have in a snapshot directory structure like the following:

- fuel-snapshot
-- `hostname`
-- `hostname`/var/
-- `hostname`/pg_dump/
-- `node-1`
-- ...

Previously (and for now) instead of `hostname`, IP address or
'localhost' (127.0.0.1) was used.

Change-Id: I8d9618590d73f93a6957ca80edc363dbd1b43c61
Depends-on: Iafecfa458372458963abd1e16890fe225454a612
Closes-bug: #1519303

commit_message:
Avoid to use keystone CLI in doc

Currently, the keystone CLI is deprecated in favor of
python-openstackclient.
So, this patch changes to use from keystone client to
openstack client.

Change-Id: I208184671cbebff28df07dfdf4893483524ac165
Closes-Bug: #1524123

commit_message:
Swarm: Cleanup of swarm heat template

This patch does some cleanup work in swarm heat template including description,
typo fixes, removal of default in nested template.

Also updated magnum.conf.example.

Closes-Bug: #1524134
Change-Id: Id0dd345150aba4cf88df5a7d9ac85dcbb100e3d0

In v1, when an image is in a queued state you get a 404 raised:

 $ glance image-download 1d92c891-baf7-4d3f-8213-67e924421275 | cat
 404 Not Found: The resource could not be found.: Image  1d92c891-baf7-4d3f-8213-67e924421275 is not active (HTTP 404)

In both v1 and v2, when you have an active zero size image that is handled fine.

In the v2 case when the image is queued, a get to /file returns a 204 (not a 200 as with an active image).

When we attempt to download non-existant data should we should catch the 204 and raise an exception (somewhat similar to what happens in the v1 case) rather than pretending we have a valid body (the same result as a zero size body case)?'}, {'account_id': 455, 'date': '2015-11-24 13:57:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 12:

The current v2 client behaviour with this patch is:

image-a) a zero size active image
image-b) a queued image

glance image-download <image-a> > out
command exit code '0', successfully creates zero size file "out"

glance image-download <image-b> > out
command exit code '0', successfully creates zero size file "out"

The CLI doesn't distinguish between these two different cases.

In contrast, when using the v2 API directly (or the v1 client library) it is possible to distinguish between these cases.

I think we need to either raise an exception or return a None body so the users of the library know when they haven't got a "real" zero size image.'}, {'account_id': 455, 'date': '2015-11-30 11:01:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 12:

commit_message:
Fix the download error when the image locations are blank

When the image locations are blank, glance client will get a http response
with no content, glance client should show user no data could be found,
instead of processing the blank response body that will lead to exception.

Glance client will also get a 204 response when an image is in a queued
state (this is true for 'master' and liberty/kilo/juno based servers).

Closes-Bug: #1472449

Co-Authored-by: Stuart McLaren <stuart.mclaren@hp.com>
Change-Id: I5d3d02d6aa7c8dd054cd2933e15b4a26e91afea1

commit_message:
Add python classifiers to setup.cfg

It is hard to understand which python version manilaclient supports
without explicit classifiers. Python 2.7 and Python 3.4 are added to 
classifiers, since they are tested in the regular gates. Python versions,
which are not tested, should not be listed in the classifiers.

Change-Id: Ifb9ce3c4f47ee29d7f0592a3205ad1b95824cc92

commit_message:
Test equality of types.String choices as a set

The equality of a String might return false if the choices value
is a List for one instance and Tuple for another.  Also the order
can prevent a valid match.  This patch normalizes the compare with
a set to ensure equality in those cases.

Change-Id: Ic5c36c390401c4cd60b1c5c46be93744b0025f06
Closes-Bug: #1523792

commit_message:
Make v2 enable_disable_user use **kwargs

As we discussed on
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-July/068864.html
All http POST/PUT methods need to contain **kwargs as their arguments.

This patch makes enable_disable_user of v2 identity_client use **kwargs.

Partially implements blueprint consistent-service-method-names

Change-Id: Ie1f6f16f25505973436adf3376e59d8574e39d44

commit_message:
Make v2 update_user_own_password  use **kwargs

As we discussed on
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-July/068864.html
All http POST/PUT methods need to contain **kwargs as their arguments.

This patch makes update_user_own_password of v2 identity_client use **kwargs.

Partially implements blueprint consistent-service-method-names

Change-Id: I032d46226b85ce40ef40a02b384e366da9ea87c5

subject: Make v2 update_user_password use **kwargs

commit_message:
Make v2 update_user_password use **kwargs

As we discussed on
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-July/068864.html
All http POST/PUT methods need to contain **kwargs as their arguments.

This patch makes update_user_password of v2 identity_client use **kwargs.

Partially implements blueprint consistent-service-method-names

Change-Id: Iaaf3e488795bf6ecd377445b74d990087d094c1a

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-12-07 19:16:24.000000000', 'message': "Do not assume galera_all hostgroup exists in galera_server role

The 'main.yml' task file found in the 'galera_server' role assumes
the 'galera_all' hostgroup exists. It uses it as a condition to run
the 'galera_setup.yml' task file which is used to initialize
the Galera cluster. This assumptions could prevent someone from reusing
the 'galera_server' role independently.

The 'galera_server_bootstrap_node' variable exists and defaults to
groups['galera_all'][0].

This change suggests using the 'galera_server_bootstrap_node' variable
so someone could override its value without the need to patch
the 'main.yml' task file.

commit_message:
Do not assume galera_all hostgroup exists in galera_server role

The 'main.yml' task file found in the 'galera_server' role assumes
the 'galera_all' hostgroup exists. It uses it as a condition to run
the 'galera_setup.yml' task file which is used to initialize
the Galera cluster. This assumptions could prevent someone from reusing
the 'galera_server' role independently.

The 'galera_server_bootstrap_node' variable exists and defaults to
groups['galera_all'][0].

This change suggests using the 'galera_server_bootstrap_node' variable
so someone could override its value without the need to patch
the 'main.yml' task file.

Change-Id: I8e810b0cdd3425c9782280c4ff1f59526dd96c0b

commit_message:
Fixes playbook runtime issues with ldap

When using an LDAP backend the plabooks fail when "ensuring.*"
which is a keystone client action. The reason for the failure is
related to how ldap backend, and is triggered when the service
users are within the ldap and not SQL. To resolve the issue a boolean
conditional was created on the various OS_.* roles to skip specific
tasks when the service users have already been added into LDAP.

Change-Id: I64a8d1e926c54b821f8bfb561a8b6f755bc1ed93
Closes-Bug: #1518351
Closes-Bug: #1519174
Signed-off-by: Kevin Carter <kevin.carter@rackspace.com>

commit_message:
update port_security_enabled API to be tri-value

This patch make port_security_enabled API to be tri-value
[True, False, 'L2ONLY'].
Boolean value True and False are compatible with the meaning before, and
'L2ONLY' is stored in a new column 'disabled_domain' of securitybinding tables,
it works when the original column 'port_security_enabled' is False.
With the new knob 'L2ONLY', we can create a unaddressed-port from a network
with subnet, but also indicate the filter remove the L3 and arp spoofing rules
when the port without IP address. And it could be the flag to inform nova to
remove the verification of network with ip and port with ip when boot a VM with
a port.

DocImpact
APIImpact

Partially Implements: blueprint vm-without-l3-address

Change-Id: If9e39b3cd75e8ac906f863d895ac37fa5ea798a5

commit_message:
Rename Meta-Action to Action

Some Python class and packages need to be renamed
for a better compliance with the shared terminology
which provides a better understanding of Watcher
objects and components by every contributor.

This patchset is there to change Meta-Action to Action

Partially implements: blueprint glossary-related-refactoring

Change-Id: Ie67b800332179be93718030ddd7a36ddc76a544c

commit_message:
Re-add store list to sample glance-api.conf

The 'stores' parameter is a comma separated list of
enabled stores. We should add the list of stores in the
comment so users can know which stores they can enable.

Change-Id: I0f8492c56c915fbf9eaa2011fa991b8150a18e16
Closes-bug: 1521236

commit_message:
Use version convert methods from oslo_utils.versionutils

oslo_utils provide version convert methods in versionutis[1],
these methods work well on Python 2.7 and Python 3.4,
so don't need maintain them.

[1]https://github.com/openstack/oslo.utils/blob/master/oslo_utils/versionutils.py

commit_message:
Leverage dict comprehension in PEP-0274

PEP-0274 introduced dict comprehensions to replace dict constructor
with a sqeuence of key-pairs[1], these are benefits:
  First, it makes the code look neater.
  Second, it gains a micro-optimization.

We dropped python 2.6 support, we can leverage this now.
Note: This commit doesn't handle dict constructor with kwargs.

[1]http://legacy.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0274/

Change-Id: Ifca656d516809a6a52cf15bac3f6361e8d83aa58

commit_message:
Fix time mocking on wait condition timeout tests

Extend the time override used when testing timeouts for wait conditions,
so that real time isn't used for waiting for the failure.

Change-Id: Ib1042fc748ecc490d315ec5a5844ceacc50534e0
Partial-Bug: #1524047

commit_message:
Make coverage tests work

The default package name for coverage doesn't work, so we need to
explicitly state it in tox.ini. We should also exclude the tests
directory as that code will typically be 100% tested, and if it's
not we don't really care.  Also excludes the coverage results from
git so it doesn't show up in git status.

Change-Id: I9e99b2c7c215a5de3c76cb2daf0f468f445774c3

commit_message:
Make server action methods[m-] use **kwargs

As we discussed on
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-July/068864.html
All http POST/PUT methods need to contain **kwargs as their arguments.
This patch makes server action methods[m-] use **kwargs.

Partially implements blueprint consistent-service-method-names

Change-Id: I8c73b6c1cbcfa0b528c45f5b2c73ce3c46abf648

commit_message:
Do not assign a value to the class variable 'widget'

Class variable 'widget' stores a default widget for CharField.
It is dangerous to change it. This patch fixes this and assigns
a value to instance variable.

Change-Id: I7220dcacd64aeee096e9340dc49bb4c5ebcfefd5
Closes-Bug: #1521535
(cherry picked from commit 88abc05d2401c1b3e163502923611c7d03c88d35)

commit_message:
Support distributed dhcp agent

This patch enables neutron support of distributed DHCP
agent. Currently this patch only works for OVS agent.

DocImpact
Related-Bug: 1468236
Partially-Implements: blueprint distributed-dhcp

Change-Id: Ic84b47cb1aae0bd50995e01bc9c83de978a31bc6

commit_message:
Remove disabled attribute from select fields on submit

Subsqeuently we get the value included in the POST-request.

Replaces custom logic implemented for subnetpools that has weaknesses and
does not work any more.

Change-Id: I5ce5ff0dcd7ba812a92e1aaa82c770064f0302c0
Closes-Bug: 1498926

commit_message:
Format time to cut microsecond

Almost for all resource creation request, some valued datetime attrs
like 'created_time' would contain microsecond, this patch makes
_fmt_time a common method and cut microsecond.

Closes-Bug: #1522324
Change-Id: I309aeca629ef50320300d695e647b42595a4c0b4

commit_message:
/NetworkDriver.CreateEndpoint cleanup

Add logic to search for port created by ipam and remove subnet creation
logic. Now subnets are created using IPv4Data and IPv6Data in
/NetworkDriver.CreateNetwork

Change-Id: I22e879dad662d8f7b060e9dad9977727569d467e
Closes-Bug: #1521111

commit_message:
Create subnets in /NetworkDriver.CreateNetwork using IPv4Data and IPv6Data

Currently subnets are created in ./createEndpoint but to be compatible
with latest libnetwork changes , subnets should be created in
/NetworkDriver.CreateNetwork.

Change-Id: I3b436d391d9d6aa57d5b8b09b1bcf6ba2d613e30
Closes-Bug: #1520744

commit_message:
IPAM: Implement /IpamDriver.ReleaseAddress

This api will be invoked by libnetwork to release an previously
allocated IP address. IpamDriver will delete the corresponding neutron
port to release address.

https://github.com/docker/libnetwork/blob/master/docs/ipam.md#releaseaddress

Change-Id: I41a2621ac081749a32f589c0d056042f986175c7
Partially-Implements: blueprint remote-ipam-driver
Closes-Bug: #1521100

This patch still has the server for the kuryr-ipam, which is duplicated with kuryr and now we have two remote drivers which implement the network drivers and the IPAM drivers. It's confusing and what I meant was it's better to have the single server for two roles. /Plugin.Activate returns ["NetworkDriver", "IpamDriver"] and that's enough.

If you agree to have the single server, it seems the basic structure of the IPAM driver is the same as my patch and I think my patch can still be alive. So I'd like my patch merged first because it seems you copied and pasted my unit tests, the config code and the comments for the endpoints. At least I'd like to see Co-Authored-By tag even if my patch is not merged because I spent some time on them and you use them as they are.

https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/GitCommitMessages#Including_external_references

commit_message:
IPAM: Add /Plugin.Activate, /IpamDriver.RequestPool and placeholders

Implement /Plugin.Activate and /IpamDriver.RequestPool and placeholders
for rest of the ipam driver apis. Original patch for ipam
implementation, [1], was too big to review, so splitting that into
seperate review requests. This is first in series.

[1]: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/248042/10
https://github.com/docker/libnetwork/blob/master/docs/ipam.md

Co-Authored-By: Taku Fukushima <f.tac.mac@gmail.com>
Change-Id: Id4f01bbb53fb393ed0d5577244c782582f9014c0
Partially-Implements: blueprint remote-ipam-driver
Closes-Bug: #1520080
Related-bug: #1518249

Anyway. Marking as WIP since this needs some more discussion and review...'}, {'account_id': 3153, 'date': '2015-12-05 12:54:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

So we had this same discussion with puppet-monasca (it's now big-tent).

I honestly don't have any trouble with adding this module into Puppet OpenStack tent because I don't want this effort going to another private github repo. I prefer encouraging Community efforts and I'm glad they plan to make it.

One thing I would like to see is a patch in governance to add the module. I would like to see what TC thinks about it.

commit_message:
Support neutron QoSBandwidthLimitRule resource plugin

Provide some resources to support Neutron QoS capability.
This patch add OS::Neutron::QoSBandwidthLimitRule
resource plugin.

Change-Id: I0b28d990f9fd086eba089601c42f74bc2a9bf667
Blueprint: support-neutron-qos

commit_message:
Create bareon project

This project is to provide a flexible and easy to
use operating system installation tool. It is to focus
on providing advanced partitioning functionality as well
as advanced pre-configuration features. It differs from
existent great cloud oriented solutions like Ironic Python
Agent (OS provisioning) and Cloud init (OS pre-configuration).
It is to be a tool similar to old plain OS installation tools like
anaconda or debian-installer but dramatically more convenient.

Change-Id: Ia6c59aefb260712d34d73a49f186e072637d7de5

commit_message:
Fix Resource.__eq__ mismatch semantics of object equal

The __eq__ of apiclient.base.Resource will return True,
if the two objects have same id, even if they have different
other attributes value. The behavior is weird and don't
match the semantics of object equal. The objects that have
different value should be different objects.
Fix this issue and add some test cases in this patch.

Change-Id: If31659c503007e08baa0a23485a49a5e5dde8e8b
Closes-Bug: #1499369

commit_message:
Add subnetpool property to subnet resource

This patch adds subnetpool and prefixlen properties
to the Subnet resource. Also makes the existing cidr
property optional.

Change-Id: Id7ff95f90fef5febd9e7e4df3b96f2467c05a840
Blueprint: subnet-pools

commit_message:
Fix decription for Image create modal

Current image create modal description/helpbox
contains inaccurate description.
Glance can store compressed images, but
Nova can't boot from compressed images.
This patch deletes mentioning compressed
images as supported type.

Change-Id: Ie896cceae0b20f7d7cbe4af1e6bca67f2389c43f
Closes-Bug: #1479966

- gate-keystone-specs-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/39/254139/4/check/gate-keystone-specs-python27/00d1c3d/ : FAILURE in 2m 45s'}, {'account_id': 5707, 'date': '2015-12-08 18:01:59.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

So I personally do not think we should do Domain Specific Roles (DSR) this way - I prefer the current merged API that uses implied roles.  I think most people have now agreed that the amount of API duplication that role-groups causes is confusing in and of itself.

The other issue raises with DSRs and implied roles is that the fact that the DSR itself does not go in the token will cause confusion. I don't believe this is the case - here's the most typical scenario:

 - A public cloud provider wants to attract as many, diverse customers as possible
 - To do that, they are likely to offer a flexible, fine-grained set of roles that are encoded in policy rules
- As part of the on-boarding of a customer (represented as a domain), they will give the domain admin the spec of what roles they must assign their used to give the permission to execute various APIs.  These are set by the cloud provider, the domain admin has no control over this.
- Without DSRs the domain admin will either use this list or explain this list to their project admins for project within their domain. They'll work out (and probably circulate internally) how the set of roles defined by the cloud provider shod map onto what every usage model they have
- With DSRs, they'll encode that model in DSRs and use those (or tell their project admins to use those). So they'll be fully aware of what roles are cloud provider roles and which are DSRs. Hence, I don't see the confusion."}, {'account_id': 5707, 'date': '2015-12-08 18:03:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

(reposting with better formatting):
So I personally do not think we should do Domain Specific Roles (DSR) this way - I prefer the current merged API that uses implied roles. I think most people have now agreed that the amount of API duplication that role-groups causes is confusing in and of itself.

The other issue raises with DSRs and implied roles is that the fact that the DSR itself does not go in the token will cause confusion. I don't believe this is the case - here's the most typical scenario:

1) A public cloud provider wants to attract as many, diverse customers as possible

2) To do that, they are likely to offer a flexible, fine-grained set of roles that are encoded in policy rules

3) As part of the on-boarding of a customer (represented as a domain), they will give the domain admin the spec of what roles they must assign their used to give the permission to execute various APIs.  These are set by the cloud provider, the domain admin has no control over this.

4) Without DSRs the domain admin will either use this list or explain this list to their project admins for project within their domain. They'll work out (and probably circulate internally) how the set of roles defined by the cloud provider shod map onto what every usage model they have

5) With DSRs, they'll encode that model in DSRs and use those (or tell their project admins to use those). So they'll be fully aware of what roles are cloud provider roles and which are DSRs.

Hence, I don't see the confusion.
Add Comment"}, {'account_id': 6482, 'date': '2015-12-08 19:20:53.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Code-Review-2

based on the outcome of the last keystone meeting, let's stick with what is planned since it's the least invasive API change. if it's not working to gyee's liking we can change things up in N"}, {'account_id': 1916, 'date': '2015-12-08 19:47:25.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

I agree role groups doesn't make much sense either as we can more or less accomplish the same thing with just user groups. User groups are essentially like permission templates, aggregating multiple roles for a given target.

On the other hand, I don't think DSRs, the way it is designed right now, can offer us much value either. Like I mentioned in Keystone meeting, I am fine with make them experimental for now and see what shakes out as our role assignments are pretty messy as is right now.

1) A public cloud provider wants to attract as many, diverse customers as possible

Agreed.

2) To do that, they are likely to offer a flexible, fine-grained set of roles that are encoded in policy rules

They are only as fine-grained as the global roles they can infer. In other words, the finer grained you want to achieve, the heavier customization you'll need to make to all your service's policy.json files. You may end up with lots of global roles. Its certainly possible, but its your choice.

3) As part of the on-boarding of a customer (represented as a domain), they will give the domain admin the spec of what roles they must assign their used to give the permission to execute various APIs. These are set by the cloud provider, the domain admin has no control over this.

That's fine if you only want to group the global rules and assign them more meaningful names. But then again, whoever have the permission to assign roles, can he see both global and domain-specific roles? We need to be clear about that. Right now its rather difficult to enforce between those who can assign global roles and those who can only assign DSRs.

4) Without DSRs the domain admin will either use this list or explain this list to their project admins for project within their domain. They'll work out (and probably circulate internally) how the set of roles defined by the cloud provider shod map onto what every usage model they have

Go back to my previous question, whoever have permission to assign roles, which roles can they see and assign? And how do we enforce that? I presume you want to hide the global roles in some way?

5) With DSRs, they'll encode that model in DSRs and use those (or tell their project admins to use those). So they'll be fully aware of what roles are cloud provider roles and which are DSRs.

You are hinting there's an element of role hiding in here. But the spec wasn't clear on how that is accomplished. If project admin have access to both global roles and DSRs, then I can't possibly see any value in DSRs."}, {'account_id': 5707, 'date': '2015-12-09 09:14:00.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

The decision is to implement the current (merged) API as experimental, as opposed to this one.'}]

commit_message:
An alternative to domain roles using implied roles

This is for comaparison with the current version of domain specific
roles (which uses the implied role functionality).

It has been suggested that a better API for domain specific roles
would be to define them as domain specific role groups, and
duplicate the assignment APIs to allow all the assignment actions to
use a role-group as well as a regular role.

THIS POST IS FOR DISCUSSION, DO NOT MERGE

Change-Id: Id68507747359d6800d1f45d69dacf0817665c483

commit_message:
Fix CI for stable/6.1

- pin mock in tests for Python 2.6
- pin oslo.serialization<1.5.0
- pin oslo.context<0.5.0
- pin oslo.config<=1.11.0
- pin oslo.utils<1.4.1
- pin oslo.i18n<=1.5.0
- pin networkx<1.10
- pin netaddr<=0.7.13
- pin pycadf<=1.0.0
- pin stevedore<=1.4.0
- bump gulp-lintspaces to 0.2.5

Closes-Bug: #1472018
Change-Id: I7ca9b9ff9b6329b33ab2ed4ed00d8b8a8df8ad25

owner_name: Chris Hoge (not involved in upstream development)
commit_message:
Update the list_opts documentation for new api

The config generator was updated to allow either group names or
group objects. This change updates the documentation to cover
both use cases.

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/242472/

Closes-Bug: 1395819

Change-Id: I1c4c6af50d1da3fe3ca82d8bde35c4121369b904

commit_message:
Make PortOpt accept choices parameter

It is useful to add an additional parameter of choices for PortOpt.
Port will determine if choices are valid values in range of 1 and 65535.
And only assign choices to Integer type.

Change-Id: I690ab4c57f5f67c3c8401dc74a83b8e61970da79
Depends-On: 0416d73e56511b3437a071216888bc3a19648feb

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-12-07 18:12:01.000000000', 'message': 'Make test_expiration_policy_for_executions stable

mistral.tests.unit.services.test_expired_executions_policy
ExpirationPolicyTest.test_expiration_policy_for_executions
occasionally fails - depending on the runtime length of the
unit tests.

The fix is to move the initialization of WF_EXECS (which also
initializes the created_at and updated_at properties) from the
global init section of the file into the _load_executions method
so the created_at and updated_at properties will be updated with
values that are relative to the beginning of the current test and
not the load of the python file.

Change-Id: I7f17d8086bbef05fb4e8a32fbf872c683b021ccf
Partial-Bug: #1506199
'}]
commit_message:
Make test_expiration_policy_for_executions stable

mistral.tests.unit.services.test_expired_executions_policy
ExpirationPolicyTest.test_expiration_policy_for_executions
occasionally fails - depending on the runtime length of the
unit tests.

The fix is to move the initialization of WF_EXECS (which also
initializes the created_at and updated_at properties) from the
global init section of the file into the _load_executions method
so the created_at and updated_at properties will be updated with
values that are relative to the beginning of the current test and
not the load of the python file.

Change-Id: I7f17d8086bbef05fb4e8a32fbf872c683b021ccf
Partial-Bug: #1506199

commit_message:
Speed up test for software config transport update

The recent test_server_update_software_config_transport is waiting for a
RPC timeout to finish, while ignoring the error. This uses a mock for
the RPC client to speed things up.

Change-Id: I40bf6e28ce52caf903cdec6c6afb91a5cee8c868

commit_message:
Delete python bytecode before every test run.

This should eliminate the need to clean -x -i to kill pyc files in
your local directory to get tests to pass.

Change-Id: Ia6f81dfd1c6487c293012623a165d9dd474b0f4f
Closes-Bug: #1368661

commit_message:
Deprecate the pki and pkiz token providers.

Upon making fernet the default token provider, we
should deprecate pki and pkiz due to a security
vulnerability. Deprecation should be in favor of fernet.

implements: bp deprecated-as-of-mitaka
Change-Id: I469758029a9e89e7cdcbac4445eab8eedd6c2859
Depends-On: I34b7b7c34fa34551c0fdf9bdeb1ffaa432c10adc

commit_message:
Fix race condition when changing passwords for admin tests

In a previous fix, Ied83448de8af1b0da9afdfe6ce9431438215bfe0, we applied a
sleep in order to mitigate a race condition in keystone with Fernet tokens.
This change moves that same concept to the tempest.api.identity.admin.v3 tests
so those pass with Fernet as well.

This change also separates the token from the v2 update user password response
in test_user_update_own_password() for the same reason. By isolating the token
from the update user call, we ensure we don't hit the same issue with the v2
update user password tests.

Change-Id: I34b7b7c34fa34551c0fdf9bdeb1ffaa432c10adc
Closes-Bug: 1473567
Related-Bug: 1517697

commit_message:
Don't hold the connection when reply fail

This change moves the reply retry code to upper layer
to be able to release the connection while we wait between
two retries.

In the worse scenario, a client waits for more than 30 replies
and died/restart, the server tries to send this 30 replies to this
this client and can wait too 60s per replies. During this
replies for other clients are just stuck.

This change fixes that.

Related-bug: #1477914
Closes-bug: #1521958

(cherry picked from commit I0d3c16ea6d2c1da143de4924b3be41d1cea159bd)

Conflicts:
	oslo_messaging/_drivers/amqpdriver.py
	oslo_messaging/_drivers/impl_rabbit.py

Change-Id: I492b82082a372763e60cf06ce0b8135ade7a6e71

commit_message:
Partition preservation scope for RF

Cover reinstall procedure for Reduced Footprint feaure:

1) fuel node --node 1 --disk --download
2) edit disk.yaml (set keep_data to true)
3) fuel node --node 1 --disk --upload
4) provision virt node
5) spawn vms (fuel2 env spawn-vms <env-id>)
6) wait for VMs to comes up
7) deploy virt node

Change-Id: I0c00000453d16d14c28d10f87d066d9890181db0
Closes-Bug: #1505147
(cherry picked from commit 58209947cd0d1cd564017020d6f6ee12fb0fd7ec)

commit_message:
New projects should come constraint enabled.

We are now in widespread deployment mode for constraints. Having the
cookiecutter show how its done is useful, as well as saving new
projects from any headaches.

Change-Id: Ie3d16d22bf28d0c64e5b36ea4be92f612bb56eca

commit_message:
lb: Correct String formatting to get rid of logged ValueError

The following error is caused by a missing String formatting in the
linuxbridge agent:
"ValueError: unsupported format character 'a' (0x61) at index 90
Logged from file linuxbridge_neutron_agent.py, line 447"

In addition a duplicated word in the log text has been fixed.

Change-Id: I587f1165fc7084dc9c4806149b65652f6e27b14e

Scenario:

15. Repeat steps 11-14 40 times

17. Boot vm3 in network1
18. ping 8.8.8.8, vm1 (both ip), vm2 (fixed ip) and vm3 (fixed ip)
    from each other vm

commit_message:
Add testcase 'Ban l3-agent many times'

Testcase checks that neutron router will be alive and will work after
ban 2 l3-agents and then 40 times ban and clear last l3-agent.

Scenario:
1. Revert snapshot with neutron cluster
2. Create network1, network2
3. Create router1 and connect it with network1, network2 and
   external net
4. Boot vm1 in network1 and associate floating ip
5. Boot vm2 in network2
6. Add rules for ping
7. ping 8.8.8.8, vm1 (both ip) and vm2 (fixed ip) from each other
8. Ban l3-agent on what router1 is
9. Wait for route rescheduling
10. Repeat steps 7-8
11. Ban l3-agent on what router1 is
12. Wait for L3 agent dies
13. Clear last banned L3 agent
14. Wait for L3 agent alive
15. Repeat steps 11-14 40 times
16. Boot one more VM (VM3) in network1
17. Boot vm3 in network1
18. ping 8.8.8.8, vm1 (both ip), vm2 (fixed ip) and vm3 (fixed ip)
    from each other vm

Change-Id: I9a233cceb39d01586c7ae2d9ba56b56bda7297be
Closes-Bug: #1523827

commit_message:
Add testcase 'Drop rabbit port and check l3-agent'

Testcase checks that neutron router will be rescheduled and will work
after drops rabbitmq port on controller node.

Scenario:
1. Revert snapshot with neutron cluster
2. Create network1, network2
3. Create router1 and connect it with network1, network2 and
   external net
4. Boot vm1 in network1 and associate floating ip
5. Boot vm2 in network2
6. Add rules for ping
7. ping 8.8.8.8, vm1 (both ip) and vm2 (fixed ip) from each other
8. with iptables in CLI drop rabbit's port #5673 on what router1 is
9. Wait for route rescheduling
10. Check that router moved to the health l3-agent
11. Boot one more VM (VM3) in network1
12. Boot vm3 in network1
13. ping 8.8.8.8, vm1 (both ip), vm2 (fixed ip) and vm3 (fixed ip)
    from each other

Closes-Bug: #1523776
Change-Id: I53f8d3b1f3923375e34640f1b69724d2ee56a9ea

commit_message:
Move L3 test cpecific logic to it own test case

All existing L3 agent tests has same initial steps:

1. Revert snapshot with neutron cluster
2. Create network1, network2
3. Create router1 and connect it with network1, network2 and
   external net
4. Boot vm1 in network1 and associate floating ip
5. Boot vm2 in network2
6. Add rules for ping
7. ping 8.8.8.8, vm1 (both ip) and vm2 (fixed ip) from each
   other

This common steps now extracted from neutron tests base class and placed
in new TestL3AgentBase class. Now neutron base test class contains only
common methods.

Closes-Bug: #1523778
Change-Id: I856312af33d912ace524b3c2e70ef8e400145dcf

commit_message:
Add testcase 'Ban l3-agents and then restart first'

Testcase checks that neutron router will alive and will be on
cleared node after ban all l3-agents and then restart the first one

Scenario:
1. Revert snapshot with neutron cluster
2. Create network1, network2
3. Create router1 and connect it with network1, network2 and
   external net
4. Boot vm1 in network1 and associate floating ip
5. Boot vm2 in network2
6. Add rules for ping
7. ping 8.8.8.8, vm1 (both ip) and vm2 (fixed ip) from each
   other
8. Ban l3-agent on what router1 is
9. Wait for route rescheduling
10. Repeat steps 7-8
11. Ban l3-agent on what router1 is
12. Clear first banned L3 agent
13. Check that router moved to the health l3-agent
14. Boot one more VM (VM3) in network1
15. Boot vm3 in network1
16. ping 8.8.8.8, vm1 (both ip), vm2 (fixed ip) and vm3
    (fixed ip) from each other

Closes-Bug: #1523773
Change-Id: I8a53202c362b046623db6868980d7fbe42a9071b

"}, {'created': '2015-12-08 06:15:43.000000000', 'message': "Add automated testcases 'ban some l3-agents'

Testcase checks that neutron router rescheduled after twice ban l3 agent
on same node as router is.

Scenario:
1. Revert snapshot with neutron cluster
2. Create network1, network2
3. Create router1 and connect it with network1, network2 and
   external net
4. Boot vm1 in network1 and associate floating ip
5. Boot vm2 in network2
6. Add rules for ping
7. ping 8.8.8.8, vm1 (both ip) and vm2 (fixed ip) from each other
8. get node with l3 agent on what is router1
9. ban this l3 agent on the node with pcs
    (e.g. pcs resource ban p_neutron-l3-agent
    node-3.test.domain.local)
10. wait some time (about 20-30) while pcs resource and
    neutron agent-list will show that it is dead
11. Check that router1 was rescheduled
12. repeat steps 8-11
13. Boot vm3 in network1
14. ping 8.8.8.8, vm1 (both ip), vm2 (fixed ip) and vm3 (fixed ip)
    from each other

Closes-Bug: #1523542
Change-Id: I41041a21d91dd46b7202a7093f0181eb0e500bab

commit_message:
Add automated testcases 'ban some l3-agents'

Testcase checks that neutron router rescheduled after twice ban l3 agent
on same node as router is.

Scenario:
1. Revert snapshot with neutron cluster
2. Create network1, network2
3. Create router1 and connect it with network1, network2 and
   external net
4. Boot vm1 in network1 and associate floating ip
5. Boot vm2 in network2
6. Add rules for ping
7. ping 8.8.8.8, vm1 (both ip) and vm2 (fixed ip) from each other
8. get node with l3 agent on what is router1
9. ban this l3 agent on the node with pcs
    (e.g. pcs resource ban p_neutron-l3-agent
    node-3.test.domain.local)
10. wait some time (about 20-30) while pcs resource and
    neutron agent-list will show that it is dead
11. Check that router1 was rescheduled
12. repeat steps 8-11
13. Boot vm3 in network1
14. ping 8.8.8.8, vm1 (both ip), vm2 (fixed ip) and vm3 (fixed ip)
    from each other

Closes-Bug: #1523542
Change-Id: I41041a21d91dd46b7202a7093f0181eb0e500bab

commit_message:
Add automated testcases 'ban one l3-agent'

Testcase checks that neutron router rescheduled after ban l3 agent
on same node as router is.

Scenario:
1. Revert snapshot with neutron cluster
2. Create network1, network2
3. Create router1 and connect it with network1, network2 and
   external net
4. Boot vm1 in network1 and associate floating ip
5. Boot vm2 in network2
6. Add rules for ping
7. ping 8.8.8.8, vm1 (both ip) and vm2 (fixed ip) from each other
8. get node with l3 agent on what is router1
9. ban this l3 agent on the node with pcs
    (e.g. pcs resource ban p_neutron-l3-agent
    node-3.test.domain.local)
10. wait some time (about 20-30) while pcs resource and
    neutron agent-list will show that it is dead
11. Check that router1 was rescheduled
12. Boot vm3 in network1
13. ping 8.8.8.8, vm1 (both ip), vm2 (fixed ip) and vm3 (fixed ip)
    from each other

Closes-Bug: #1523522
Change-Id: Icef087cc83bd5cff0971cea4a66a8cef9cf4cffb

commit_message:
Use proper decode function name.

os.fdecode is not a real thing, os.fsdecode is.

Change-Id: I20b3b6d15b7d5775e1f6f97190d9acc62ca3a4ca

User Guide Reorganization for Mitaka

The information architecture and content of the user guides
needs updating. This spec outlines the proposed changes.

Implements: blueprint user-guides-reorganised

[{'created': '2015-11-19 11:26:08.000000000', 'message': 'basic API service

Implement the basic boilerplate for the smaug APIs, using WSGI and
OSLO services.
Smaug-api service now can respond the request of the resource plans.

Follow these steps to using smaug API service:

1 download the source code form github.

2 install dependency libraries
pip install -r requirements.txt

3 install smaug API service
python setup.py install

4 start smaug API service
python /usr/local/bin/smaug-api --config-file /etc/smaug/smaug.conf

4 using the resource plans RESTAPI (now only available with auth_strategy  noauth )
http://10.229.46.128:8799/v1/55daed3cc6da42c6aa25e55d15bb1757/plans

Closes-Bug: #1514745
Change-Id: Id27c624714c1839818937b94c1ecd33f393ec282

commit_message:
basic API service

Implement the basic boilerplate for the smaug APIs, using WSGI and
OSLO services.
Smaug-api service now can respond the request of the resource plans.

Follow these steps to using smaug API service:

1 download the source code form github.

2 install dependency libraries
pip install -r requirements.txt

3 install smaug API service
python setup.py install

4 start smaug API service
python /usr/local/bin/smaug-api --config-file /etc/smaug/smaug.conf

4 using the resource plans RESTAPI (now only available with auth_strategy  noauth )
http://10.229.46.128:8799/v1/55daed3cc6da42c6aa25e55d15bb1757/plans

Closes-Bug: #1514745
Change-Id: Id27c624714c1839818937b94c1ecd33f393ec282

commit_message:
Enable HA mode for mesos bay in Magnum

To create a HA mesos bay, users need to specify at least 3 master
nodes. For example:

magnum bay-create --name mesosbay --baymodel mesosbaymodel \
                  --master-count 3

Change-Id: I85c2113fec0fd743cc3b142e6a490bdfb3b896e6
Implements: blueprint mesos-multi-master-node

commit_message:
Enable HA mode for mesos bay in Heat templates

Support a cluster of master nodes, which tolerates failure of no more
than half number of nodes. The setup requires manually write down
IP addresses of all master nodes, which is impossible by using
cloud-init. Therefore, it replaces cloud-init with
SoftwareDeploymentGroup.

Using SoftwareDeployment requires to build additional packages into
the image [1]. The image building instruction has been updated for
that.

[1] http://docs.openstack.org/developer/heat/template_guide/
software_deployment.html#software-deployment-resources

Partially-Implements: blueprint mesos-multi-master-node
Change-Id: I34b85680803ea6070df94a6bccee3d677b8bfaab

I am okay with removing iso8601 from requirements if it's not being used.
But I don't think we should remove the debug level from the conf files.

Following are the reasons :-

1. iso8601 is indirectly used by keystone client and removing the log level would result in numerous debug messages from that library in glance-api logs .
e. g. while validating user tokens

2015-12-04 17:28:09.224 DEBUG iso8601.iso8601 [-] Parsed 2015-12-05T02:28:08.000000Z into {'tz_sign': None, 'second_fraction': u'000000', 'hour': u'02', 'daydash': u'05', 'tz_hour': None, 'month': None, 'timezone': u'Z', 'second': u'08', 'tz_minute': None, 'year': u'2015', 'separator': u'T', 'monthdash': u'12', 'day': None, 'minute': u'28'} with default timezone <iso8601.iso8601.Utc object at 0x7f88ce566890> from (pid=31097) parse_date /usr/lib/python2.7/dist-packages/iso8601/iso8601.py:184
2015-12-04 17:28:09.224 DEBUG iso8601.iso8601 [-] Got u'2015' for 'year' with default None from (pid=31097) to_int /usr/lib/python2.7/dist-packages/iso8601/iso8601.py:140
2015-12-04 17:28:09.224 DEBUG iso8601.iso8601 [-] Got u'12' for 'monthdash' with default 1 from (pid=31097) to_int /usr/lib/python2.7/dist-packages/iso8601/iso8601.py:140
2015-12-04 17:28:09.225 DEBUG iso8601.iso8601 [-] Got 12 for 'month' with default 12 from (pid=31097) to_int /usr/lib/python2.7/dist-packages/iso8601/iso8601.py:140
2015-12-04 17:28:09.225 DEBUG iso8601.iso8601 [-] Got u'05' for 'daydash' with default 1 from (pid=31097) to_int /usr/lib/python2.7/dist-packages/iso8601/iso8601.py:140
2015-12-04 17:28:09.226 DEBUG iso8601.iso8601 [-] Got 5 for 'day' with default 5 from (pid=31097) to_int /usr/lib/python2.7/dist-packages/iso8601/iso8601.py:140
2015-12-04 17:28:09.226 DEBUG iso8601.iso8601 [-] Got u'02' for 'hour' with default None from (pid=31097) to_int /usr/lib/python2.7/dist-packages/iso8601/iso8601.py:140
2015-12-04 17:28:09.226 DEBUG iso8601.iso8601 [-] Got u'28' for 'minute' with default None from (pid=31097) to_int /usr/lib/python2.7/dist-packages/iso8601/iso8601.py:140
2015-12-04 17:28:09.227 DEBUG iso8601.iso8601 [-] Got u'08' for 'second' with default None from (pid=31097) to_int /usr/lib/python2.7/dist-packages/iso8601/iso8601.py:140

2. The glance-api & other configs are generated and not a good idea to manually edit it. The value for default_log_levels is from oslo_log which sets some sane log level values for certain libraries. e.g. suds in DEBUG mode can dump raw XML's and hence it was decided to keep it at INFO. Thus, similarly for iso8601. https://github.com/openstack/oslo.log/blob/ca3cbe8970dcfa1c3117f0fe2b3e4be2359703fe/oslo_log/_options.py#L110

Please let me know what you think and as always thanks for improving the code :)"}, {'account_id': 8157, 'date': '2015-12-08 19:58:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
Remove iso8601 dependency

Glance does not import and use this module directly, no need to list
it in the requirements and no need to set debug level.

Closes-Bug: #1520358
Change-Id: Idc7581903b8b6962c3fb6c51dace3142c707d420

commit_message:
Cap elasticsearch client <2.0

The elasticsearch 2.0 python client is not backwards compatible
with 1.x, nor with server versions prior to 2.0 (and similarly, the
1.x client cannot be used with server versions after 1.x). See
https://elasticsearch-py.readthedocs.org/en/master/ for details.

Since devstack installs elasticsearch 1.x it seems sensible to cap
the client version. Deployers using version 2.0 will need to install
that client version in projects requiring it.

Change-Id: I78c18185a6cdaf3acf51e84c5475aa6ff29c5e1f
Partial-Bug: #1515412

commit_message:
Scheduler: honor the glance metadata for hypervisor details

The scheduler would not honor the glance image metadata for
'hypervisor_type' and 'hypervisor_version_requires'. This was due
to the fact that this was not part if the image_meta object.

Change-Id: I03742cc9330814e2758184d8189a5be93a2b978b
Closes-bug: #1523503

commit_message:
Remove pypy env from tox

We removed pypy's gate a few weeks ago as it's been failing for some
time. This means we're not supporting it anymore. Therefore, it should
be ok to remove it from the tox file.

Change-Id: Iac9bf4775794b8d097c0c5cae0337f14fa2fa25c

subject: Avoid RequestContextSerializer from oslo.messaging
messages:
[{'account_id': 6773, 'date': '2015-12-08 18:07:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

Thanks *waits for jenkins*'}, {'account_id': 14629, 'date': '2015-12-08 18:07:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Build failed. For 3rd party ci contact info: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/ThirdPartySystems

- gate-tempest-ironic-ilo-driver-iscsi_ilo https://15.184.134.36/90/254890/1/check/gate-tempest-ironic-ilo-driver-iscsi_ilo/dc2dd0f : FAILURE in 1m 50s'}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2015-12-08 18:33:44.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

This is not a bug fix. This is also a fix for a future removal of a thing that was not deprecated in liberty, from what I can tell. So to remove it from any version of oslo.versioning that stable/liberty is picking up would be a backward incompatible failure.

Things are probably not a problem in stable/liberty now because stable/liberty upper-constraints is at 2.5.0:

https://github.com/openstack/requirements/blob/stable/liberty/upper-constraints.txt#L195

But that's prone to change if we don't have test coverage for this in the stable/liberty constraints checking jobs."}, {'account_id': 10343, 'date': '2015-12-08 18:57:16.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

Abandoning in favor of https://review.openstack.org/#/c/254904/'}, {'account_id': 5638, 'date': '2015-12-09 06:02:21.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Longer term this is exactly what oslo.messaging team wants ironic to do. This works with both older and newer oslo.messaging libs. So i don't understand what the pushback is about."}, {'account_id': 5638, 'date': '2015-12-09 06:03:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Irrespective of what we decide about oslo.messaging pinning, reverts, this should go into stable/liberty for ironic IMHO'}]

[{'created': '2015-12-08 18:05:52.000000000', 'message': 'Avoid RequestContextSerializer from oslo.messaging

Oslo.messaging is in the process of removing the class
starting with the change id:
I21d76abf1c30b9e89cb8a6c20d1c0cc79cd83a3f

So ironic should just use its own class. Note that the
next oslo.messaging release will break ironic based on
some local testing.

Change-Id: I618fdc3024b3bc16515216bda900804f4cebba7d
(cherry picked from commit 37d36f1536944de38a0f7a726e625b893088e1be)
'}]
commit_message:
Avoid RequestContextSerializer from oslo.messaging

Oslo.messaging is in the process of removing the class
starting with the change id:
I21d76abf1c30b9e89cb8a6c20d1c0cc79cd83a3f

So ironic should just use its own class. Note that the
next oslo.messaging release will break ironic based on
some local testing.

Change-Id: I618fdc3024b3bc16515216bda900804f4cebba7d
(cherry picked from commit 37d36f1536944de38a0f7a726e625b893088e1be)

commit_message:
Update migrate_volume API to use versionedobjects

The following patch updates migrate_volume,
migrate_volume_completion, and update_migrated_volume
APIs to use volume versionedobjects.  Changes were
made to be backwards compatible with older RPC clients.
It only includes changes to the core cinder code.
Changes in the drivers are left to each driver
maintainer to update.

Note that this patch DOES NOT try to use object dot
notation everywhere, since it would increase the
size of the patch.  Instead, it will be done in
subsequent patches.

Change-Id: I21fe68193c934a7ef3688274ab35f664a08cac7e
Partial-Implements: blueprint cinder-objects
Closes-Bug: #1521085

commit_message:
Pass dict into update() rather than **kwargs

It looks like in the keystone/tests/core.py file 'ref', which is
a dictionary declared in most of the methods, is being updated by either
passing a dictionary or passing kwargs. To me it doesn't make
sense to make keyword arguments out of a dictionary, to wind up
adding them to another dictionary. This patch changes these so
update() is called passing in a dictionary instead of keyword args.

e.g. dict.update(dict1)

Change-Id: Iaec993c4728e82d6b27d8862005fa319daae3bb0

commit_message:
Refactor test use of new_*_ref

The new_*_ref functions were confusing because while some of them
used the base new_ref() function, the ones that use it were often
removing fields anyways. Then there were other new_*_ref functions
that didn't use new_ref() at all. So new_ref() is removed and the
functions just create the dict that they need.

Change-Id: I5bde0007802523a582fe0c93c4d07345c4407afc

commit_message:
Allows type-create to return dict instead of list

CLI output for command "type-create *" used to return list of one element
But should return info as dictionary as it is for all other resources.
Hence made the changes.

Change-Id: I5da7a97b116873aebc7d8746c216da3c5bfc84da
Closes-Bug: #1446700

commit_message:
Adds host_capabilities CRUD API operations

HostCapabilities is a database model containing host features or
capabilities that could be scheduled for instances that require them.

Adds CRUD operations for the new host_capabilities table.

Partially-Implements: blueprint expose-host-capabilities

Change-Id: I5ac69c0757a3642320984320921376c6e9dafb1c

commit_message:
Add py34 to tox.ini

Add py34 to tox.ini.
if encounter with error 'db type could not be determined',
please remove .testrepository/ and .tox/ first, then run
'tox -e py34'

commit_message:
Delete python bytecode before every test run.

This should eliminate the need to clean -x -i to kill pyc files in
your local directory to get tests to pass.

Change-Id: Ida103931d2ccb1e84fef06a29192ed43959ac15c

commit_message:
Update coverage to keystoneauth1

The .coveragerc file was pointing to the keystoneauth directory which no
longer exists. Update this to keystoneauth1.

Also remove the keystoneauth/openstack directory. This doesn't exist as
we don't have anything from oslo.incubator.

Change-Id: Icc4a4680bb9af5c2bfa230a5ffcf508740c06aae

commit_message:
Make  add_sample  use **kwargs & doc string update

As we discussed on
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-July/068864.html
All http POST/PUT methods need to contain **kwargs as their arguments.

This patch makes add_sample of telemetry_client use **kwargs.
Also update doc string for the same.

Partially implements blueprint consistent-service-method-names

Change-Id: I9a863d13319701362a5d364cb0a4afc6868d9f8f

commit_message:
policy restrain non-admin user image upload

There are some conditions exist where policy restrain the non-admin user to
update image in glance, in such conditions tempest test cases fails.

For catering this requirement new flag was introduced in tempest.conf
'image_upload_allowed' under [image] section. Its default value is true,
but in case non-admin user is not allowed to perform image upload,
value can be set to false, so that test cases are skipped rather
then getting failed.

Change-Id: I36899afa808fbc605968e96efbf9de347f95a17e
Closes-Bug: 1510905

commit_message:
Make cluster actions API return a location header

This patch makes some cluster actions return a location header.
* add/del nodes
* scale in/out
* policy attach/detach
* policy update

commit_message:
Make node-create return a location header

This patch makes node-create response return a location
header for node resource. Node is treated as a resource,
so action_id is not returned.

commit_message:
Add accessIPv4 and accessIPv6 when create server

nova support accessIPv4 and accessIPv6 as input param
but nova client don't support it as input param when
doing create operation.
Because it's already support in v2.1 so no microversion
introduced.

Change-Id: Idd50fe921f8c931ee28902f90ffdde6bfba34359
Closes-Bug: 1522359

commit_message:
Fix H404/405 violations in novaclient/v2/[a-f]

There is a lot of H404/405 violations in novaclient, and it is better
to fix those to have a better doc string for class/methods.

This patch fixes these violations for [a-f] files under  novaclient/v2
folder.

As there are lot of violations and cannot be fixed in single patches,
So separating those in multiple patches for easy review.

Change-Id: Ibe5afef349d1be6d70903e06bee402ca30738ea1
Partial-Bug: #1521899

commit_message:
Run py34 env first when launching tests

To resolve "db type could not be determined" when running tox
for the first time py34 environment need to laucnhed before py27.

commit_message:
Fix H404/405 violations in novaclient/tests/*

There is a lot of H404/405 violations in novaclient, and it is better
to fix those to have a better doc string for class/methods.

This patch fixes these violations for files under  novaclient/tests/
folder.

As there are lot of violations and cannot be fixed in single patches,
So separating those in multiple patches for easy review.

Partial-Bug: #1521899
Change-Id: I6e712ece14c745013bfba0bee9d77e7875dd2263

[{'created': '2015-12-08 18:49:07.000000000', 'message': 'Fix format of existing network in _get_or_create_network()

When running scenarios with the existing_networks plugin,
_get_or_create_network() returned the network object itself rather
than the Neutron-like return value of a dict with a single "network"
key, whose value was the network object. This fixes that error, and
adds an assertion to ensure that all return values from
_get_or_create_network() are of the correct format.

Change-Id: I94a6bf6c1dae8060f7644dad36ea72a81a8b0701
'}]
commit_message:
Fix format of existing network in _get_or_create_network()

When running scenarios with the existing_networks plugin,
_get_or_create_network() returned the network object itself rather
than the Neutron-like return value of a dict with a single "network"
key, whose value was the network object. This fixes that error, and
adds an assertion to ensure that all return values from
_get_or_create_network() are of the correct format.

Change-Id: I94a6bf6c1dae8060f7644dad36ea72a81a8b0701

commit_message:
[Neutron] Fix _get_or_create_subnets() return value

neutron.utils.NeutronScenario._get_or_create_subnets has
a bug - if given network already has subnets then return
value is list of str, but should be list of dicts.

This is fixed, and proper unit test is reworked too

Change-Id: I5815c1f58437ec0de90a6a0350d5434a83c9bbc1

commit_message:
Use FakeVolume in server test cases.

We have a class FakeVolume to fake one or more volumes. So use it in
test_server.py.

commit_message:
Use FakeImage in server test cases.

We have a class FakeImage to fake one or more images. So use it in
test_server.py.

Change-Id: I276e4ade5aecefbe66b9722c1dfbac10b3bd14b6
Implements: blueprint improve-image-unittest-framework

commit_message:
Migrate network client to SDK.

The previous patches have migrate all network commands to
the new version using sdk. This patch will remove the
temporary method, and implement a new make_client() to
create sdk network client.

And also, find() in openstackclient/network/common.py must
support sdk. The logic of this function will become much
easier than before, so this patch also removes two useless
test cases of find().

This patch will also remove the patched methods in tests.

Change-Id: Ic2f7bca073beb9757172d16f95d9b82c48cbbc12
Implements: blueprint neutron-client
Co-Authored-By: Terry Howe <terrylhowe@gmail.com>
Co-Authored-By: Tang Chen <tangchen@cn.fujitsu.com>

subject: Migrate "network show" command to use SDK.

commit_message:
Migrate "network show" command to use SDK.

This patch makes "network show" command use sdk.

Since we have to keep the other commands runnable with
the old network client, we use a temporary method to
create sdk network client. And as a result, the tests
need to patch a method to fake the temporary method,
which will be removed at last.

There are two same test cases in the unit tests. This
patch will remove one.

And since the output has changed, we also need to fix
function test cases.

Change-Id: I4c06b4efad2db430767bbaa882b0876df3ab483a
Implements: blueprint neutron-client
Co-Authored-By: Terry Howe <terrylhowe@gmail.com>
Co-Authored-By: Tang Chen <tangchen@cn.fujitsu.com>

commit_message:
Migrate "network set" command to use SDK.

This patch makes "network set" command use sdk.

Since we have to keep the other commands runnable with
the old network client, we use a temporary method to
create sdk network client. And as a result, the tests
need to patch a method to fake the temporary method,
which will be removed at last.

Change-Id: I794ac4b82d9200747298f1a9ee44611140e9b6d0
Implements: blueprint neutron-client
Co-Authored-By: Terry Howe <terrylhowe@gmail.com>
Co-Authored-By: Tang Chen <tangchen@cn.fujitsu.com>

commit_message:
Fix the endpoint of /v2 on concept doc

As the folloing content of etc/nova/api-paste.ini, legacy v2
endpoint is /v2, not /v2.1.

 /v1.1: openstack_compute_api_v21_legacy_v2_compatible
 /v2: openstack_compute_api_v21_legacy_v2_compatible
 /v2.1: openstack_compute_api_v21

So this patch fixes the endpoint.

Partially implements blueprint complete-todo-in-api-concept-doc

Change-Id: I6d9346ced38f522c516778cadae217d1d5c9cff1

commit_message:
tighten regex on objectify

There are some strange and wonderous work arounds in the json loader
for samples templates to do with templated values which are ints. This
was always kind of a hack, but when attempting to add a replacement
value in the middle of a string it was clear that the anchoring for
this regex was wrong.

Update the begin anchor to be ': ' instead of [^"], which would match
anywhere inside a string.

Change-Id: I9811b34d58a4d4cf7f181689b25212893880dcf4

commit_message:
Migrate "network delete" command to use SDK.

This patch makes "network delete" command use sdk.

Since we have to keep the other commands runnable with
the old network client, we use a temporary method to
create sdk network client. And as a result, the tests
need to patch a method to fake the temporary method,
which will be removed at last.

Change-Id: I1f2c404e4b0ff6727e4c535ce543aa406f2290ce
Implements: blueprint neutron-client
Co-Authored-By: Terry Howe <terrylhowe@gmail.com>
Co-Authored-By: Tang Chen <tangchen@cn.fujitsu.com>

Hi, everyone.

There is another way to fix this bug:

Since the 'disk size' info is always unavailable to cluster storage system like ceph and sheepdog, we should consider this as a normal scenario. We can modify the SIZE_RE from 
r"(\d*\.?\d+)(\w+)?(\s*\(\s*(\d+)\s+bytes\s*\))?" to 
r"(\d*\.?\d+)(\w+)?(\s*\(\s*(\d+)\s+bytes\s*\))?(unavailable )?"
when parse the 'disk size' info ,if we find it is unavailable , then simply set it to zero or other reasonable value. This can keep my correction to a minimum.

Looks for your advice, I need your help, thank you very much!'}, {'account_id': 18967, 'date': '2015-11-20 07:06:19.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 18967, 'date': '2015-11-20 07:13:25.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 18967, 'date': '2015-11-20 07:17:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-11-13 17:11:14.000000000', 'message': 'Improve the imageutils.QemuImgInfo class to parse image info more exactly

The current imageutils.QemuImgInfo class parse all the image info
at first, but if one of the info is unavailable, it would raise a
ValueError.

Sometimes, user only care one of the info which is really
available, but it may be failed because of the ValueError which is
caused by another unavailable info.

This patch resolved the problem by parse each of the info separately,
so that getting the info which is cared would not be influenced by
other unavailable info.

commit_message:
Fix the bug of can't get the desired image info

When we use 'qemu-img info' command to get image info, some kinds
of image may show an 'unavailable' disk size. For example:

$qemu-img info sheepdog:volume-1af1afa0-7820-4063-9b90-4fa6161a74a9
image: sheepdog:volume-1af1afa0-7820-4063-9b90-4fa6161a74a9
file format: raw
virtual size: 10G (10737418240 bytes)
disk size: unavailable

$qemu-img info -f rbd rbd:data/foo
image: rbd:data/foo
file format: rbd
virtual size: 10G (10737418240 bytes)
disk size: unavailable
cluster_size: 4194304

The current code didn't consider 'unavailable' size, and it will
raise a ValueError in this case. This patch fixed this bug by
adding the judgment of 'unavailable' size.

Change-Id: Ic5f3b80e172baaafc07432319f8aa24bf117b392
Closes-Bug: #1516083

commit_message:
Make policy-create show result policy correctly

Response from policy-create is not parsed correctly, this patch
fixes the issue.

Closes-Bug: #1522324
Change-Id: I58a0959a852ff48dbb1f8db378b13fb2ce6696ad

commit_message:
Migrate "network create" command to use SDK.

This patch makes "network create" command use sdk.

Since we have to keep the other commands runnable with
the old network client, we use a temporary method to
create sdk network client. And as a result, the tests
need to patch a method to fake the temporary method,
which will be removed at last.

Change-Id: I06559c675be1188747257f72f18d6b4d420d0285
Implements: blueprint neutron-client
Co-Authored-By: Terry Howe <terrylhowe@gmail.com>
Co-Authored-By: Tang Chen <tangchen@cn.fujitsu.com>

commit_message:
Try to show policy after policy created

Try to show policy after policy created, like what we do after
profile created, so that we can display created_time.

Closes-Bug: #1522324

commit_message:
Cluster's timeout is in seconds not minutes

In the help msg of cluster_create and cluster_update, timeout is
described in minutes, but actually it's in seconds, this patch
fixes the issue.

Closes-Bug: #1523791
Change-Id: I8bb1f1da59aad902f2bb5068dc941f09e17cc638

- gate-neutron-specs-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/29/205429/1/check/gate-neutron-specs-python27/f2a8290/ : SUCCESS in 2m 30s'}, {'account_id': 11682, 'date': '2015-07-24 14:04:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

You are going to have to persuade me of several things:
1) that lease state can be shared to avoid separate instances handing out the same address (or are you going to partition the lease space)?
2) that the traffic generated by lease information being shared between the dDHCP instances isn't >> the raw DHCP traffic it is replacing.
3) that the additional load on the compute node(s) is worth the load on the network node(s)"}, {'account_id': 9444, 'date': '2015-07-25 11:12:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

(5 comments)

as an op I like the idea, but for simplicity I think all dhcp agent for should have all the network information for the network it serves

I can live with more load on computes (after all a dhcp agent is less load than a small vm) but the dhcp agent should know all about the network it serves, I don't want failed reboot after migration cause of this.

great feature :)"}, {'account_id': 8976, 'date': '2015-07-27 02:13:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

@Ryan Moats, thanks very much for your review, your question is just this proposal want to solve, so I am very glad to answer them:
1. your are right, the lease space will be partitioned to distributed dhcp agents, in other words, every distributed dhcp agent on compute nodes just get the VMs lease which this compute node serve. 2. the traffic generated by lease information in one compute node
will not go out this node(for openvswitch agent, I plan to use flow table to implement it) 3. as description in this spec, just there is/are VMs in a compute node, the distributed dhcp agent will spawn dnsmasq process for related network, for example, there are 
two computes named A and B which running distributed dhcp agents, if there are two VMs in a network, but all these two VMs boot on compute A, just compute A will spawn dnsmasq process, if these two VMs boot separately on compute A and compute B, these two nodes will all spawn dnsmasq process, but compute A just get VM A lease info, compute B just get VM B lease info. so in conclusion, the load on compute node(s) will low than network node(s).'}, {'account_id': 8976, 'date': '2015-07-27 02:27:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(5 comments)'}, {'account_id': 9970, 'date': '2015-07-27 04:09:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

I like the potential of this change.  I look forward to seeing patch sets implementing this functionality.  Hopefully this work can be completed in Liberty.'}, {'account_id': 11682, 'date': '2015-07-27 12:44:46.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Then please add the address partition statement to the spec as it wasn't clear to me."}, {'account_id': 11682, 'date': '2015-07-27 12:46:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Edit to above comment (hit publish too soon).  Also, the partitioning assumption needs to discuss *how* the available leases will be partitioned as well as what happens if one dDHCP agent runs out of leases while another still has some.'}, {'account_id': 8976, 'date': '2015-07-29 08:45:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

hi Ryan Moats, your question is about upgrade? do you mean how to upgrade from a common dhcp agent to distribued dhcp agent? When distributed dhcp agent restarts, it will just get its lease info from neutron-server, so after upgrading, just need delete the old dhcp port, it will create a new distributed dhcp port and notify all distributed dhcp agent to update'}, {'account_id': 11682, 'date': '2015-07-29 13:59:11.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

No, I wasn't asking about upgrade - if the subnet lease space is partitioned between dDHCP agents, then you need to explain what will happen when the partition in one dDHCP agent is exhausted, but other dDHCP agents still have available leases."}, {'account_id': 8976, 'date': '2015-07-30 09:04:05.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

hi Ryan Moats, thanks very much for your review and suggestion. Now in Neutron, when user create a port, neutron-server will allocate a MAC and IP for this port, then neutron-server send this information to DHCP agent, this mechanism is same in distributed dhcp agent, so there is no this problem that 'the partition in one dDHCP agent is exhausted, but other dDHCP agents still have available leases', I have submit patch #https://review.openstack.org/#/c/184423/, if you are interested in it, please help to review it."}, {'account_id': 11682, 'date': '2015-07-30 14:21:02.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

(3 comments)

Ok I'll grant that exhaustion isn't an issue

commit_message:
Distributed DHCP Agents

Distributing the DHCP across compute nodes will
offer better scalability and limit the failure
domain of the IPAM service.

Related-Bug: 1468236

Change-Id: I12d8af4820488880998ffe964d10c649d66ab834

commit_message:
Make add_router_to_l3_agent use **kwargs

As we discussed on
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-July/068864.html
All http POST/PUT methods need to contain **kwargs as their arguments.

This patch makes add_router_to_l3_agent of network client
to use **kwargs.

Partially implements blueprint consistent-service-method-names

Change-Id: I2f17062076a3a356bbb2f67099bcc9b3edd2f76f

Add documentation for network RBAC feature

This adds some documentation for the new policy engine
added to Neutron and its initial use case of sharing
Neutron networks with specific tenants.

commit_message:
Bumps os-win version to 0.0.7

os-win 0.0.7 has been released. Some of the changes are:

Adds method for checking if disk is attached.
Adds Python 3 compatibility.
Adds exception and unused arguments cleanup.
Adds virtual disk IOPS limits setter.
Caches Windows version. The  HyperVDriver will load faster.
Adds method to set VM boot order.

Change-Id: Id742202cd2c412e5e8c84951b6215206b25c18ee

commit_message:
Remove invalid comment about LDAP domain support

LDAP does not and will not support domain CRUD.

There is a test in test_backend_ldap.py checking
that domain CRUD is returns 403 Forbidden.

This patches removes a comment that said that
test should be removed once domain CRUD is
supported by LDAP; which is invalid.

Change-Id: I359790025cc412ef87d406fd07dc8cd60afe07d2

commit_message:
Pull project out of request in addition to tenant

Keystone V3 renamed tenant to project. In order to deal with keystone
V3, start pulling X-Project-Id from the headers.

Since keystonemiddleware authtoken sets both X-Project-* and
X-Tenant-*, we don't need to look up X-Tenant-*.

Don't do anything with renaming the internal variables - that will come
later.

Change-Id: I5e27cf6a54fb603b81d41b8b4f085d59354627fb
Depends-On: I1f754a9a949ef92f4e427a91bbd1b1e73e86c8c4
Closes-Bug: #1503428

commit_message:
Make param description & LogInfo better

*Replace 'the execution of a benchmark scenario' with 'the task
 execution' in Line 265.
 Since 1) we do not widely use term `benchmark';
       2) actually the whole task is being stopped, not only
          specific scenario.
*Some param's descreption not unified.

Change-Id: Iabc0718002c1d14cb3f8da9a99ad9991c967a833

commit_message:
Rename get_db_flavor_details to show_db_flavor_details

[GET /resources] methods should be "list_<resource name>s"
or "show_<resource name>", so this patch applies the rule
to flavors client

Partially implements blueprint consistent-service-method-names

Change-Id: I3a1ad587af43f5177b9d7d95a3c2170a4b1224c0

commit_message:
Reset the compute_rpcapi in Compute manager on SIGHUP

This links Service.reset() to the manager, which for compute will
rebuild the compute_rpcapi and thus re-determine the appropriate
RPC versions.

Change-Id: Ifec7f6ff604d1e5f3663633065e9a55baacffec8

commit_message:
Initial patch for Trircle stateless architecture

Initial patch to implement the framework of Tricircle, this is
the part for Nova api gateway and Cinder api gateway, keystone
authentication integrated.

Change-Id: I7e33948d4850cf1eabeb9c865fc79c2475323988
Blueprint: https://blueprints.launchpad.net/tricircle/+spec/implement-stateless

commit_message:
Load the 8021q kernel module in simple-init

Vlan support was recently added to glean. However, if the 8021q module
is not loaded, glean will fail to bring up a tagged interfaced defined
in /etc/network/interfaces.d/. Manually attempting to bring up the
interface results in an error[1]. This patch ensures that the 8021q
module is loaded so that tagged interfaces can be brought up at boot.

[1] http://paste.openstack.org/show/480027/

Change-Id: I15d805c07d4b5e1161d831f0393d027e4325137f

commit_message:
Pass environment variables of proxy to tox

When a development environment is under a proxy, tox is failed even if
environment variables of the proxy are set.
This patch fixes this problem.
See:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/189569
Closes-Bug: #1465086
Change-Id: Iafd49c8f9c11561dd85820367eaf2cb6b19a7aeb

commit_message:
Help msg about libvirt always default device names

Supplying a device name for any of the block devices specified as part
of the `nova boot` or `nova volume-attach` call will not be honoured by
any libvirt compute nodes.
We should modify documentation make this more clear.

Change-Id: I3209c2829225492df25ff9ab9098071372957bd5
Closes-Bug: 1479214

commit_message:
[V3] Rename get_region to show_region

[GET /resources] methods should be "list_<resource name>s"
or "show_<resource name>", so this patch applies the rule
to region client

Partially implements blueprint consistent-service-method-names

Change-Id: I5fc446b2e5f8931a1a8b27b0db03956a0e3ad8b2

I'm so glad to see someone attempting to fix this, its been a thorn in my side for a while. I've had a work around though and that was to use the localboot element from the tripleo-image-elements repo, as it already understands how to handle this error: 

http://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack/tripleo-image-elements/tree/elements/localboot

There seems to be a lot of duplication between that element and this grub2 one. The localboot code seems like it covers more edge cases too. We shouldn't be maintaining this logic in two different places.

I can confirm that this fix works though :D"}, {'account_id': 18542, 'date': '2015-11-19 08:39:18.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

@Sam Betts

Although the two file have some similar logic, but localboot is in another repo. I don't quite understand the relationship between   diskimage-builder repo and tripleo-image-elements repo. 

It seems not a good solution to ask user must add localboot with grub2+ubuntu element to avoid the issue.
So I still prefer to fix it in grub2 element."}, {'account_id': 6637, 'date': '2015-11-19 09:23:59.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

tripleo-image-elements is just a bunch of elements designed for tripleo for use with disk-image-builder.

I wasn't suggesting that people use the localboot element. What I was suggesting is that if localboot is a more complete solution then we should take that code and put it in the grub2 element, so that the tripleo guys can just use the grub2 element instead of maintaining their own version."}, {'account_id': 10511, 'date': '2015-11-19 10:25:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Code-Review+1

@Sam,

It seems that in tripleo-image-elements/localboot, there are other  features, such as install grub-pc, uboot-tools than fixing the issue of install grub-efi-* failure contained in this patch. 
For me, with this patch(Fix grub-efi-amd64-signed install failure), I have verified that the ramdisk/image created via DIB can be boot successfully. 
So I am wondering whether all the functionalities in tripleo-image-element/localboot are necessary in DIB?'}, {'account_id': 6488, 'date': '2015-11-25 20:39:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Code-Review+2

commit_message:
Fix grub-efi-amd64-signed install failure

When build ubuntu iso image, it will install grub-efi-amd64-signed
and grub-efi-amd64 packages. Both of the postinst script will try
to find root device and install grub which will definitely fail in
such a chroot environment.
So the workaround is to skip error and remove postinst script.
And confirm the package be installed successfully at last.

Change-Id: Ie0aecb212b22362046db55b5ad8c64c3211c28e5
Closes-Bug: #1491280
Co-Authored-By: Jane.zhang <jian.zhang8@hpe.com>

commit_message:
Fix mocking in several tests causing excessive run-times

Several tests have missing mocking resulting in many minutes wasted
waiting for either RPC or client validation to time out.

Strangely this doesn't cause the tests to fail, only waste a lot of
time (tox -e py27 was taking over 10 mins for me, now nearer 5)

There are more broken tests to fix, but some have logical errors
so will be handled via subsequent patches.

Change-Id: I2021505930d6547a16531de6b2f9fbf33855fa3a
Partial-Bug: #1524047

"The map() thing is also a big dilemma for me all the time,"

Hehe.

"other things like items() vs iteritems() can be sorted out with six, sadly not map."

I believe that the authors of six didn't add six.map() because list comprehension already solve the problem.

For items() vs iteritems(), the question is solved: you must use items() in OpenStack:
https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Python3#Common_patterns

Thread: http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-June/066391.html

commit_message:
Port Windows drivers to Python 3

Minor changes for Python 3 compatibility in the
Windows iSCSI and SMB3 drivers.

Change-Id: I64ee3c929e4142357c076e5de91ff68c0cb3c399
Partial-Implements: blueprint cinder-python3

commit_message:
Fix dictionary key error

The key 'multipath' was being referenced in the 'connector' dictionary
in initialize_connection(), even though the key was not always set.

Change-Id: Ia3c7640a24ebe9bedec3402f6cefb7e457c66ecd
Closes-Bug: #1522062

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

commit_message:
Avoid service_instance neutron port clash in HA

Currently, after getting the list of ports from neutron,
we filter based on the device_id. In HA, two nodes will
share the same device_id. Hence, ports on different HA
backends are reported together causing a
ServiceInstanceException, not allowing for port creation
on the required backend.
This patch will use both device_id and binding:host_id
properties to filter neutron port lists to check for
valid port clashes if any.

Closes-Bug: #1519326
Change-Id: I81a16c360b1e8fffccddef5f358136e5fbde81e4

commit_message:
Remove the Metric proxy

This proxy class is not currently useful in any usable way so it just
pollutes the namespace of loaded proxy classes. It was added
to get the class started, but was not completed. Rather than offer a
proxy that only tells you what it can do but can't do anything, it's
removed. The resources that would populate a proxy class are left alone.

Change-Id: I30dbff0dbba26633d3b02ee5f0751b4224cef8f4
